title: LEGO bricks generator with graphical editor

description.text:
I have designed a generator that allows to design LEGO compatible bricks of any shape using a very simple to use online editor (nothing to install on your PC). This can be used to print anything, from basic standard bricks such as a 2x2 one, to complex shapes that don't exist in the LEGO catalog. Look at the example STL files provided in the "Thing Files" section above.

The online editor can be accessed here : http://bricks.lapinoo.net

I think its usage is straightforward. Draw your brick on the editor and then choose to generate either a standard height brick, a thin brick or a base plate. No programming knowledge is needed, all is done visually. Just ask if something is unclear.

For standard height bricks, you can choose to add reinforcements in the bottom cavity of the brick, so that there are less chances that the bottom cylinder structures will break over time. Type 1 reinforcement adds some small walls around the bottom cylinders. Type 2 reinforcement fills most of the bottom cavity, while still keeping mating compatibility with standard LEGO bricks. Type 2 will probably print faster as there are less details to print and as the infill algorithms of the slicer can be used to fill the volume.

There also options to adjust some dimensions of the bricks if your printer prints some features too small or too large. Place your cursor on the ? signs in the editor for a description. I recommend that you first print a simple 2x2 brick with no adjustment and try to mate the printed brick with a standard LEGO one. Adjust then the tolerances as needed.

Note that for very large bricks the generation of the 3D model can take several minutes. This is highly dependent of the processing power of your computer. Just be patient and wait.

The generator doesn't work properly with the now obsolete Internet Explorer (unable to save the resulting STL file). Use Microsoft Edge, Google Chrome, Firefox, etc instead. Not tested on Safari, can a Mac user test it for me?

title: Diet Bearing Block With Z Probe Compatible Back Plate

description.text:
Save yourself some precious grams on the x axis and y axis with these svelt bearing blocks!

Designed to hold 8mm id linear bearings such as Igus Drylin RJ4JP-01-08, the bearings snap into the block with an interference fit. If you require extra peace of mind that they'll remain in place holes are present in the block to secure the bearings to the block with cable ties. I've been running these on my y axis without ties and the blocks hold the bearings without issue. M4 nuts are required to attach the blocks to the x and y carriages (aside from the hardware already required for standard blocks.). I'm in the process of refining the design so that the nuts are captured by the hexagonal recess to facilitate easier install.

Also included is a version of the block that allows you to mount an autolevel sensor for those of you that use rear mounted z probes that screw into the bottom block on the x carriage. Installation of the probe holder will differ depending on the probe holder design you use. I had to modify the one I was using to allow access to the screw that holds the back plate to the block I am also in the process of making refinements to the tolerances of the nut recess so that the nuts are captured, which should take some the frustration out of installing this probe mount. I may add a probe mount to the back plate to remove the need to add another one but there's a vast array of sensors used which is why I opted for a design that would allow a mount of the end user's choosing to be used. for those of you without the requisite M3 hardware to hand to attach the back plate to the block, cable ties can also be used, you will however need some M3 nuts to mount the sensor attachment to the back plate (Aside from the bolts that you were already using to attach the sensor mount to the stiock bearing blocks.).

This is a work in progress but it's in a usable state as it's installed on my A8 at the moment and working wonderfully, all planned refinements revolve around ease of installation. If you try these out feedback on any improvements I can make would be welcomed.

Print with 70% infill to ensure the bearing holders are robust enough to withstand popping the bearings in and out, they can snap off at lower infills but since there's not much material in these anyway the extra infill won't massively impact on print time. Also use supports when printing the sensor holder version.

It's also worth noting that you may need to adjust the positioning of your endstop switches to be sure that they're still triggered when you home your axes. My Y axis switch needed to be raised by a couple of mm. Just loosen the screws and pop a bit of paper/card/failed first layer under the switch. you might also have to change the orientation of the x axis endstop so that the x carriage hits the switch as the block is now too small to press it. Just unscrew the switch and flip it over. These are all things I had to do on an anet A8, your printer of course may be different.

title: iPhone X Wireless Development Stand By Zaapp, Inc.

description.text:
This stand solves a number of development challenges thanks to the new advancements is hardware and software. The stand is designed so that you can sit it on your desk while coding, run your code on device with it at a proper angle in order to be able to just look at your phone to unlock it, and be able to continue debugging when you need to test your code with other hardware.

The stand is designed so that you could use it with, or without the Qi circuit.

iOS 11 and Xcode 9 introduced the option for wireless debugging. This is an invaluable tool for working with other hardware. Zaapp is a development consulting firm located in Utah, we specialize in custom native code for IoT integration for both iOS and Android. One of our clients produces smart exercise equipment. Prior to wireless debugging, we either had to try to hold our laptops while using the exercise equipment with our phones tethered to the computer with a lightning cable, or build, disconnect, and write everything we thought we might need to debug to the log. Now we are able to debug while untethered by the lightning cable. The downside of wireless debugging is obviously not being able to charge and having your phone on constantly. This stand solves that.

For more information on Zaapp Consulting work, visit our website: Zaapp Group

Notes:

The charge circuit insert does need supports for the coil mount nub, but the stand itself can be printed without and supports and should print beautifully without them.

Both the stand and the charge circuit insert are best printed in their existing orientation. I used a clear filament for the insert so that the charge indicator light would be visible.

To glue or not to glue...

Assembly is pretty straight forward. I used a small, 5mm long 3mm cap screw to fix the PCB in place. was able to snap in the coil without any glue when printed vertically, but when printed horizontally I had to put some superglue on the coil and held it in place for a few minutes with some binder clips.

The coil backing is made out of some ceramic material that is fragile, be careful if you can snap it in place not to break the back plate. I cracked one of mine a little, but it stayed together. YMMV.

I have found that the insert should mostly snap into place and not require any glue to stay in the stand properly. Depending on your printer tolerances and the filament you use, this may not be the case. You should be able to add a little superglue to the edges of the insert and to the rear mid platform in order to secure the insert in place.

Fusion 360

This was designed using a dummy model of an iPhone X from GrabCad, an attached Canvas of the Qi circuitry inside the iPhone X from iFixit, and the rest was modeled by me.

Where to get the circuit.

The insert is modeled to fit this particular circuit. Since I am not sure how long this might be available, I hereby make an exception to the no-derivitives portion of the license for the charge circuit housing only. Feel free to find other Qi circuits an modify the insert file accordingly.

This is a portable emulation console based on a Raspberry Pi 3 and running with "Retropie".
I always wanted to build myself a raspberry pi console, but I couldn't find any suitable project for my envy: the main interest to build a console is to personalize the project. So, I decided to create mine from scratch!

I personalized various important elements, that I think we're missing on others projects:

  • Instead of classical "tactile push buttons" (which are making an horrible sound and are not very convenient to play video games), I used some Adafruit "soft tactile buttons" which are giving an impression of real controller.
  • I really wanted to let the HDMI plug accessible to be able to quickly connect it to a TV to appreciate games on widescreen. This element gave me trouble during the designing, and also for choosing a screen.
  • With the HDMI plug, I also wanted to have some USB plug in facade, so with this two interfaces it is possible to transform the console in a home console, and to allow multi-payers gaming by plugging in USB controller.

Equipment list (most of my stuff is from Banggood, but you can find them on amazon or ali-express):

  • Raspberry pi 3
  • composite TFT display, 4.3'' LCD car monitor (https://www.banggood.com/4_3inch-LCD-Car-Rearview-Monitor-Screen-Reverse-Camera-Kit-DVD-VCR-p-75120.html?rmmds=myorder&cur_warehouse=CN)
  • lithium cell charging and protection circuit (https://www.banggood.com/5Pcs-USB-Lithium-Battery-Charger-Module-With-Charging-And-Protection-p-943768.html?rmmds=myorder&cur_warehouse=CN)

description.text:
This cookie cutter set, for baking manger boxes, (Nativities), was inspired by a scroll saw pattern by Steve Good - go to http://www.stevedgood.com/catalog/ and search for "nativity box".

The photos show the various steps:
Step 1 - cut blanks and transfer to baking sheet.
Step 2 - cut and imprint layers.
Step 3 - weed layers.
Step 4 - bake and cool.
Step 5 - assemble - lid/lamb/Holy Family/donkey/stable/palm tree/lid.

If you decide to decorate any of the layers with icing, you will need the spacer, to separate them from the next biscuit.

Package in cellophane packets.

Have fun, be blessed and please upload pictures of your Advent calendars.

Notes:

My printer has a 0.5mm nozzle and I prefer to use Slic3r 0.9.9. dev with the config file I have uploaded, as the blade prints as a single extrusion, which keeps the cookie cutter strong and the blade does not delaminate, like it sometimes does, if it is printed as 2 thinner walls.

As the plastic cools in the corners it sometimes contracts and makes "high spots". If you place the cookie cutter on a marble slab, you can see light between the slab and the blade, because of these "high spots". If this happens I use 600 grit water paper on a piece of glass to sand the "high spots" back.

I use the Cookie Cutter generator by Guru to generate the individual components of the various cookie cutters.

I use Netfabb Basic to position all the individual pieces of the cookie cutter and save them in their new positions.

I use Pronteface to compose the individual pieces and then export a single composite STL.

I use Netfabb Azure cloud service to repair the cookie cutter.

The process goes as following: let it print until the last layer where it would bridge the charger part and stick your cable in there. I taped it down on the center part that's already printed and held it until 2 layers were printed.

After printing you'll notice the cable fits a bit loose. What I did is scuffing the charger cable plastic (because it's really smooth) and filled the pocket with glue then pushed it back in. Make sure it's STRAIGHT and you'll be set.

If you use a smaller iPhone (like the X) you might need to print 2 small extensions on the left and right side so it won't fall left / right. Although I use an X with it perfectly fine as is.

Good luck, and take care that the cable doesn't get stuck anywhere ;)

title: Raise3D N2 Single Extruder Cooling Duct for 40mm fan

description.text:
Replacement extruder cold zone cooling duct for use with standard 40mm fans.

This is for the SINGLE only!

After suffering through multiple failed large prints due to heat creep, and now my 2nd dead 35mm cooling fan, I hacked out this duct for using 40mm fans, and to increase airflow over the heatsink.

This mounts with three screws, one 16mm M3 which sits inside the shroud, one screw that should be your fan's depth +5mm, and then one 40mm(+/-5mm depending on fan size) screw.

Problems this solves:
The 35mm 12v fans are hard to find, but 40mm fans are plentiful (and move more air).
The stock duct left a large gap between it and the cooler, and had about 10mm of open area that didn't run across the heatsink. This part closes that gap, and brings partial wings to direct airflow across three sides of the heatsink.

Problems it creates:
You will need to use a hard to find 45mm or 50mm screw to mount this.
It deletes the part cooling portion of the Raise3d duct. The single has a standalone cooler, so this was redundant. This means you'll loose part cooling if used with a dual extruder model, or if you don't have the standalone part cooler that lives where the other extruder would be.

Loosely based on the stock cooler by Raise3d.
Increased the depth by ~13mm for better flow velocity.
Moved the output closer to the heatsink and added flow control wings to the sides.
Deleted the part cooling section.

title: 40mm Fan Intake Trumpet
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Fan intake trumpet for 40mm fans. Need two empty mounting holes. Use wood glue or even teflon for a tighter fit if necessary.

I noticed almost all of my 40mm fans created a torus of air rotation on the outter edges of the blades from poor manufacturing/design margins. This just kept air moving on the outside of the fan, and did not push as much air through as it should have been.

The trumpet adds inlet velocity and proper directional flow vectors to increase efficiency. Perfect for your filament cooling fans that have small outlets. Normally those styles reduce fan throughput flow enough that the torus flow effect is increased, so adding a trumpet increases cooling ability!

I recomment printing with ABS and doing some acetone smoothing to the surface for decreased wall roughness.

description.text:
Bakelite is an early plastic.
It is a thermosetting phenol formaldehyde resin, formed from a condensation reaction of phenol with formaldehyde.
It was developed by the Belgian-American chemist Leo Baekeland in Yonkers, New York, in 1907.

One of the first plastics made from synthetic components, Bakelite was used for its electrical nonconductivity and heat-resistant properties in electrical insulators, radio and telephone casings and such diverse products as kitchenware, jewelry, pipe stems, children's toys, and firearms. The "retro" appeal of old Bakelite products has made them collectible.

Bakelite jewelry was most popular during the Art Deco period, which began in 1909 and lasted until the 1940s. These pieces were created as costume jewelry, as a way to dress up clothing or an outfit without spending a lot of money. The pieces were popular during the heyday of the Art Deco period and many of the pieces remain popular today.

The height of Bakelite jewelry was the late 1930s, up until the end of the Art Deco period. The designs were quite popular in mass merchandise stores such as Sears and Roebuck. However there were also some famous names working with the material and creating Bakelite jewelry including Chanel and Van Cleef and Arpel. Oddly enough Bakeland allowed the patent to expire and the Catalin Corporation bought it. They began creating their own Bakelite jewelry marketed as Bakelite-Catalin. The pieces were sold in both expensive stores like Saks Fifth Avenue and smaller stores such as Woolworth’s. Bakelite jewelry was available in a variety of colors, but brown, green, red, and white were the most popular color choices.

Racing drones arent just about fun, its a serious sport. So the goal with an 3d printer should be to improve the drone. Its easy and cheap to build several parts to experiment and get the best out of the drone.

My goal was a cover to improve the flight behavior. The cover i made is based on the concept of a golfball. The plan is to reduce the air turbulence.

One of many experimental possibilities with an 3d printer.

Edit:
Version 2

I got told, that im not the first one with the Golfball idea. So i had to make some changes.
Now im more convinced about the capabilities of an 3D printer for developing parts for the Teal Drone Sport. Its always possible to improve his concept and doesnt take much time to implement his idea to a finished part.

The improved cover is still based on the Golfball concept. But now there little walls around the rotors to prevent the airflow of each rotor to disturb the neighboring one. So the air of the rotor can better flow. And the outer airstream can still flow over the golfball dots.

Another importent think is to print it with a very low filling percentage to get a lower mass. Even with a thin outer wall it should be stable enouth, the dots accomplish the stability. This is another advantage of 3D printing, you can build lightweight parts.

It's a coffee cup I want to cast in aluminium, with the surface keeping some of the "spun" effect of the 3D printer yet allowing me to polish the inside a bit smoother.

Print. Leaving base covered in casting cone, Dip in fine alumina plaster. Coat in heatproof plaster. Coat in some sturdy fibruous fireproof plaster. Invert & remove base plug. Heat through to 100C. Raise to 500C. Right, and pour in molten metal. Jiggle to remove gas bubbles. Leave to cool. Smash plaster, screw & tap plug & spin to polish inside manually. Grind off plug. Sand & water-blast. Do you figures keep tripping over things? Too much clutter in the headquarters? Make them some wire shelves to keep things nice and orderly.

There are a few variations here- small (25mm), medium (50mm) and large (70mm) shelves, but you can use the customizer to make shelves to a custom dimension.

I've also included two different lengths of upright poles (50mm and 80mm), but you can use our customizable basic cylinder to create custom lengths. If you do, be sure to set the radius to 1.5mm. Alternatively, any 3mm rod will work just as well.

If you like this sort of thing and want to see more, be sure to follow us on Twitter and/or join the discussion on our Facebook page

There are small gaps in the cylindrical parts of the shelves, in order to allow them to spread a bit to accommodate the uprights. The gap is small, though, so you'll likely want to run an exacto knife between them before attempting to insert the uprights.

It can be a bit tricky to get everything level- I recommend adding all of your shelves to your poles and sliding things around until the shelves are level. Once that's as you like it, add a drop of superglue to each of the places where a shelf touches an upright to make things permanent.

Enjoy!

title: 1940s Desk with working drawers and secret compartments (1/18 scale)

description.text:
A proper desk for private detectives and investigators of all kinds, with both working drawers to keep things tidy as well as two secret compartments to hide valuables and important documents. Just remove the snap-in panels to open up the hidden areas.

Print the desk, two each of drawer_top and drawer_bottom, one of drawer_middle, and two of whichever panel works better (see comments below). Also included is a plated version of the drawers.

I've also included a swanky blotter to give the desk a bit more of a vintage feel. I recommend giving that a bit of paint after printing to produce the proper leather and green (or whatever color you like) felt appearance.

If you like this sort of thing and want to see more, be sure to follow us on Twitter and/or join the discussion on our Facebook page

Notes:

You'll need to use a bit of support to print the desk. I recommend giving ample room between the supports and the model so that they'll be easy to remove. Otherwise, you'll likely have to spend quite a bit of time cleaning things up in order to be able to snap the panels in.

Also, note that there are two versions of the panels available. The normal panel file might be a bit loose, so I've also included a tighter option. Which one works better will depend a bit on your printer, but they're quick prints. My advice is to start with the normal panel, and if that's too loose to stay in the desk, try printing the tight version and shaving it down with an exacto knife until it just fits.

description.text: This attachment is simple and effective with many applications. I have never seen a drone that emits smoke so I wanted to provide a model that can be used for fun or for real world applications.Smoke signals can save someones life by signaling to law enforcement of a problem. They can also be used for fun such as a drone air show! This clever design enables users to 3-D print the attachment and use various smoke emitters to show off their true colors!

If I win the challenge I will edit and upload more details on ideal print settings for this part. But I did use (0.2 mm layer height, 5 solid bottom layers, 3 solid top layers, a skirt 1 mm away from part to prime the extruders with 3 layers, 15% infill, fan cooling on the 12th layer, etc) Let me know if you have any questions or suggestions!

Smoke Emitter for this design

I based the design off of a simple and cheap smoke emitter I found online.
Found here: https://inspectusa.com/smoke-emitter-perfumed-1200-cubic-feet-s104-min-pack-p-1202.html

This is the name and specifications for the emitter. The cartridge needs to be inserted into the drone and then ignited which is why it wont fit fully into the case to avoid melting of the plastic body. I chose this because they are lightweight, small in size, cheap, and emit smoke for 3 to 4 minutes of flight time!

A simple wire can be used to fasten the emitter into the cavity of the rocket. The wire will not melt and can be adjusted for different emitters with similar diameter.

My Method for Design

I noticed that nobody has ever made a legitimate smoke emission attachment for any drone. I wanted the design to be simple and effective as well as aerodynamic and stable. I added small fins to the design to help reduce drag and holes on the fins for a special reason. The smoke emitters that are suggested for the design must be inserted and lit so they do not fall all the way down into the extruded cut. The holes on the fins are used in order to fasten the smoke emitter into the attachment. The end of the emitter may get hot so instead of using plastic, a small metal wire or even paper clip can be bent and wrapped into the fin holes and around the emitter to keep it from sliding out. The drone wont be under heavy gravitational force so the emitter should remain inside the designed case.

comments.text: The smoke in the model is just for aesthetics (: the actual emitter will fit inside almost all the way and can be fastened with a small metal wire! Thanks for checking out my model!
